title.narrative: 001 CP SYSTEM STRENGTHENING, PROTECTIONFROM VIOLENCE AGAINST CHILDREN & ADOLESCE

description.narrative: By 2025, key child protection actors have in place a resilient child protection system relevant in development and humanitarian contexts with protective, promotive and responsive services that protect children from violence, exploitation, abuse and harmful practices., which contributes to Prevention Of Harmful Practice, Promotion Of Care, Mental Health And Psychosocial Well-Being And Justice, Protection From Violence, Exploitation, Abuse And Neglect, Protection From Violence, Exploitation, Abuse And Neglect (Covid). UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Public Engagement, Community Engagement, Social And Behaviour Change, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Evaluations, Research And Data, Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind, United Nations Working Together. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: 'By 2025, children in Ethiopia in both development and humanitarian contexts have legal identity and are safe and protected from violence, exploitation, abuse and harmful practices.

description.narrative: UNICEF, as part of its system strengthening effort, supported the Ministry of Women and Social Affairs and its regional bureaus to deploy1,160 social service workers –including 38 mental health and psychosocial specialists for the northern Tigray responseto provide child protection services through roll out of case management services across development and humanitarian contexts. UNICEF supported the Ministry of Justice (MoJ) to develop five-year (2021-2026) National Strategy and Plan of Action on Violence Against Women and Children and One-stop centres (OSCs) Standard Operating Procedure (SOP).UNICEF also provided financial and technical support for the development of Alternative Childcare Directive | Status:Met | As-of Date:07/01/2022
